[Are the hats merely part of her new L.A. persona, along with the many
ultra-thin Capri cigarettes]44 [she smokes,]45 [the parties]46 [she
throws for 500 people,]47 [the Chekovian feasts]48 [she offers guests
at her weekend place in Santa Barbara?]49

["No, darling,"]50 [she said recently in her fluent, slightly affected
English, during a trip East]51 [to promote Movieline's national
expansion.]52 ["You have to be born with it.]53 [I used to wear hats
in Russia,]54 [but I had to make them and my dresses.]55 [On the hat
side I wasn't getting what I wanted."]56

[Now 48 years old, Ms. Volokh has definite ideas]57 [about what she
wants.]58 [At Movieline, she wants "specific paragraphing, specific
tone, a specific attitude]59 [-- bright and bold and
tongue-in-cheek."]60 [In restaurants]61 [(in this case, the Russian
Samovar, a New York restaurant]62 [operated by and for Soviet
emigres),]63 [she didn't want the chirpy, folkish music bouncing
through the room.]64 ["You people here think]65 [this is Russian
music,"]66 [she said with disdain,]67 [and called over to the
waitress:]68 ["Could you turn it off?"]69

[That done,]70 [Ms. Volokh spoke with rampant eloquence about the many
attributes]71 [she feels]72 [she was born with:]73 [an understanding
of food, business, Russian culture, human nature, and parties.]74
["Parties are rather a state of mind,"]75 [she said,]76 [pausing]77
[only to taste and pass judgment on the Georgian shashlik]78 [("a
little well done, but very good").]79 ["If you are born]80 [to give
parties,]81 [you give parties.]82 [Even in Russia we managed to give
